VThe premises of Sri Sankara Matham witnessed an absorbing violin recital by AIR Visakhapatnam staff artiste M. Srinivasa Narasimha Murty last Sunday. He was given invigorating support by his wife, Dr. Pantula Rama, who also played the violin, M. Sridhar on the mridangam and P. Meher Sagar on the ghatam.After getting off to a tunefully brisk start with the Hamsadhvanivarnam, he playedNiravadhisukhada(Ravichandrika) andSabhachaleswaramof Dikshitar (Bhupalam) before he presentedNeeducharanamule(Simhendramadhyamam) with scholarly adornments ofaalapanaandswaramin the two tempos. After playingSarasarasamaraikasoora(Kuntalavarali) in thrilling tempo, he came out with an elated essay ofSankarabharana ragam, a vibrantthanamand an eruditely structuredpallaviconcluding with scintillatingswaramin the two tempos.Sridhar and Sagar, who were lending invigorating support, executed a well-structuredthanion the mridangam and the ghatam at this point. The presentation ofAlakalallalaada(Madhyamavathi) and athillanaof Swathiturunal in Sindhu Bhairavi constituted the concluding part. Rama proved herself a peer of her husband in all aspects of exposition of Carnatic music on the violin and its dexterous handling with acumen.
